Dear Parents/Guardians,

In an effort to prepare for possible extended closure, the West Central School District is looking for your feedback on resources you have available in the home for connecting to learning. If we are called to have school closure for an extended period of time, we intend to provide remote learning access for all of our students. This remote learning access will count as contact hours for your students, meaning that their attendance and participation in the work is required.

Please take the time to fill out the following survey (one survey per household) to help us cater instruction to your students. We would greatly appreciate if you could fill out this survey by 12:00pm tomorrow (3/17). If you are unable to fill out the form electronically please call the schools direct line at 605-528-6229. The line will be open from 5:00 PM ‚Äì 9:00 PM today, March 16 and 8:00 AM to 12:00 PM March 17.

COVID-19 Superintendent Update - 3:00pm

March 11th, 2020

3:00pm- West Central School District will be closed on Thursday, March 12th and Friday, March 13th. District facilities will be closed until Monday, March 16th. All activities, meetings, and practices are canceled through Sunday, March 15th.

While the South Dakota Department of Health has determined schools need not close, we are committed to completing a thorough cleaning of district facilities and transportation vehicles. School will resume on Monday, March 16th. The end of the 3rd quarter will now be Wednesday, March 18th.

This is the final announcement for today. Further updates will be sent as needed.

Brad Berens
West Central Superintendent

COVID-19 Superintendent Update - 1:00pm

March 11th, 2020

1:00pm- A team of West Central building administrators, supervisors, and our school nurse continue to monitor the COVID-19 situation within our district. A meeting was held with leaders from community childcare centers to share CDC and South Dakota Department of Health recommendations that we are implementing in the West Central Schools.

A phone conference is scheduled with the South Dakota Department of Health this afternoon. Information will be provided after the phone conference. We appreciate your patience and will get you information as soon as it becomes available.

Brad Berens
West Central Superintendent

At 7:30am this morning, West Central School District administration met with county officials to discuss a district action plan in response to the report of a Hartford resident with school-age children testing positive for COVID-19. The adult male identified has not been on district property within the last week.

In consultation with the CDC, South Dakota Department of Health, the Governor‚Äôs Office, and local officials, an action plan has been developed to mitigate the potential spread of COVID-19. The district has initiated steps to deep clean all school buildings and sources of transportation. All district buildings are closed and all activities are canceled for today. This includes outside groups who have reserved facility space for Community Education and/or practices.

Please stay tuned to media outlets for further updates and information coming regularly throughout the day.

Brad Berens
West Central Superintendent

post_text:
It's Read Across America Week!!! There are many great things planned this week to celebrate and encourage reading! üìö

To start us off, here is a list of the dress-up days:

Monday:
‚ÄúSleep Book Day‚Äù -- Wear your comfiest clothes!

Tuesday:
‚ÄúRead My Shirt‚Äù Tuesday -- Dress up in a shirt that you can ‚Äúread‚Äù with fun sayings on it!
**They must be school appropriate**

Wednesday:
‚ÄúWacky Wednesday‚Äù -- Dress in mismatched clothes, wacky hair, etc.

Thursday:
‚ÄúThe Cat in the Hat Day‚Äù -- Wear your favorite or wackiest hat!

Friday:
‚ÄúFox in Socks Day‚Äù -- Wear your craziest, most fun pair of socks!

Advisory teachers will count each day how many students are dressed up - one point per student per day. At the end of the week the advisory with the most points wins! Each grade level will have a winner. The teacher counts too!! üòÜ

Be sure to have a book with you every day! There will be opportunities to "get caught" reading and we will be having DEAR (Drop Everything and Read) time every day this week!

post_text: As we have concluded our Veteran's Day fundraiser to sponsor FOUR veterans to take a Midwest Honor Flight, we want to take one last opportunity to thank the local businesses and members of our community that foster the type of generosity and respect that we witnessed at today's WCMS Veteran's Day Program!
text: As we have concluded our Veteran's Day fundraiser to sponsor FOUR veterans to take a Midwest Honor Flight, we want to take one last opportunity to thank the local businesses and members of our community that foster the type of generosity and respect that we witnessed at today's WCMS Veteran's Day Program!

post_text:
Here are a few highlights and fundraiser totals. More pictures will be posted soon!
Thanks to our community, students, and most importantly our veterans, today's program was an enormous success. Through the help of several area businesses and the donations from throughout the community, our students raised $1500, enough to sponsor two veterans to take an Honor Flight. BUT...Dave & Co. Realty and First Manufacturing each sponsoring an additional Honor Flight, means WCMS has exceeded their goal and will be sending FOUR veterans to DC to visit their memorials. We are so grateful to our veterans today and every day. Happy Veteran's Day!

Through the help of several area businesses and the donations from throughout the community, our students raised $1500, enough to sponsor two veterans to take an Honor Flight. BUT...Dave & Co. Realty and First Manufacturing each sponsoring an additional Honor Flight, means WCMS has exceeded their goal and will be sending FOUR veterans to DC to visit their memorials. We are so grateful to our veterans today and every day. Happy Veteran's Day!

post_text:
Today we'd like to recognize Adam DeJong, who owns the Hartford Pizza Ranch and was a generous supporter in our Midwest Honor Flight fundraiser. Adam tirelessly supports the West Central School District and the community of Hartford.
Here is a description of Adam‚Äôs service in his own words: I spent 8 years in the South Dakota Army National Guard, all with the 1/147th Field Artillery B Battery based out of Salem, South Dakota. My MOS was 13B which was a cannon crewman where we worked on the self-propeller Howitzers. Later, we transitioned to 13M Multiple Launch Rocket System. I was a rocket launcher driver and gunner. I achieved the rank of Specialist E4 before I was honorably discharged.

Great job, 8th graders! A big thank you to Sheriff Milstead (and all of our participating community members) for sharing your time with our students!

Meet WC's Army National Guard Recruiter and someone who has played a major role in planning this year's Veterans' Day Program!
Here's a little bit about Dave Peck in his own words:
I joined the South Dakota Army National Guard 24 years ago in Salem, SD. I've served in several positions from field artillery, human resources, combat engineer, human resources, military police and medical administration. I deployed to Iraq in 2007-2008 performing convoy security and base defense as a convoy commander and squad leader. My recent position is a recruiter for SD Army National Guard. I am looking forward to providing people with the opportunity to serve, gain job experience and get an education.

‚ÄºÔ∏è‚ÄºÔ∏è‚ÄºÔ∏èHOMECOMING FRIDAY REMINDER‚ÄºÔ∏è‚ÄºÔ∏è‚ÄºÔ∏è
We run an abbreviated schedule on Friday in order to accommodate the students attending the parade and pep rally. The parade starts at 1:30 and students return to classrooms following the parade. We then attend the pep rally which generally ends about 3:30.

Students are required to attend all of the school sponsored activities that day and stay until the end of the pep rally. The buses will run on the regular schedule. The only way students are excused from the activities prior to the end of the day is if they are picked up by a parent or an adult designated by the parents. Due to the chaos around the parade and the many people in town that day, students are not dismissed to walk home or ride their bikes home after the parade. Notes, emails or calls can be directed to Sara Jost if you intend to have someone pick up students prior to 3:30. Please contact Sara by the end of day Thursday, September 19th. Thank you!

post_text:
West Central‚Äôs Music Education Program Receives National Recognition

Hartford, SD- April 19, 2018 ‚Äì West Central has been honored with the Best Communities for Music Education designation from The NAMM Foundation for its outstanding commitment to music education.

The Best Communities for Music Education designation is awarded to districts that demonstrate outstanding achievement in efforts to provide music access and education to all students.

This award recognizes that West Central is leading the way with learning opportunities as outlined in the Every Student Succeeds Act (ESSA). The legislation guides implementation in the states and replaces the No Child Left Behind Act (NCLB) which was often criticized for an overemphasis on testing-while leaving behind subjects such as music. ESSA recommends music and the arts as important elements of a wellrounded education for all children

post_text:
Parents and Guardians:

Homecoming is this Friday. We run an abbreviated schedule that day in order to accommodate the students attending the parade and pep rally. The parade starts at 1:30 and students return to classrooms following the parade. We then attend the pep rally which generally ends about 3:30.

Students are required to attend all of the school sponsored activities that day and stay until the end of the pep rally. The buses will run on the regular schedule. The only way students are excused from the activities prior to the end of the day is if they are picked up by a parent or an adult designated by the parents. Due to the chaos around the parade and the many people in town that day, students are not dismissed to walk home or ride their bikes home after the parade. Notes, emails or calls can be directed to Sara Jost if you intend to have someone pick up students prior to 3:30.

Please let me know if you have any questions.

Mr. Rockafellow

post_text:
WCMS Student Council challenged their peers to make care packages for local charities. WCMS Students were told that if they created a care package in their advisory class they could earn a ticket to a Talent Show on the last day of school. We gave the advisory classes a charity that they could sponsor - The Berakhah House (homeless shelter for veterans) Bishop Dudley House (Homeless Shelter), Hartford Food Pantry, The Humane Society, Sanford Children‚Äôs Hospital - "The Castle‚Äù, and the Minnehaha County Regional Juvenile Detention Center. The students stepped up to the challenge in their advisory classes. Each WCMS advisory created a care package. Over $1,000 in supplies and money were donated.
On Friday, May 8, 2015 the WCMS Student Council loaded up all of the care packages and delivered them. We did random acts of kindness for strangers along the way.
Some of the random acts of kindness included buying drinks for strangers at Starbucks, sharing cake pops to construction workers and a delivery man and picking up some trash in the Hartford park.

post_text:
Did you know?
Around 10 million people are reported to drive under the influence of illegal drugs every year.
After alcohol, THC, the active ingredient in marijuana, is the substance most commonly found in the blood of impaired drivers, fatally injured drivers, and motor vehicle crash victims.
Studies in several localities have found that approximately 4 to 14 percent of drivers who sustained injury or died in traffic accidents tested positive for THC.
Be more than a statistic. Don‚Äôt do drugs or get into a car when someone has been using.

post_text:
Did you know?
Kids who start drinking young are seven times more likely to be in an alcohol-related crash.
One in six teens binge drinks, yet only 1 in 100 parents believe his or her teen binge drinks.
Car crashes are the leading cause of death for teens, and about a quarter of those crashes involve an underage drinking driver.

post_text:
Did you know?
A quarter of teens respond to a text message once or more every time they drive.
20 percent of teens and 10 percent of parents admit that they have extended, multi-message text conversations while driving.
In America about 9 lives are lost a day and over 3,000 every year due to distracted driving.
Students and parents will get chance to experience Simulated Reality driving simulators during conferences.

WC Middle School and High School students from Student Council, SADD, Improv and TATU spent the morning learning about 4-D Drunk, Drugged and Distracted Driving. The message of the day seemed to be that our actions have consequences. Sometimes the consequences of 4-D are tragic like death and injury. Some times the consequences of 4-D are stressful like problems with the law. Other times, like today, consequences are good! Good things will come from the good work these teens are doing. We look forward to seeing what ideas they bring back to WC to make our roads safer!
#WhyIBuckle #SeatBeltsSAVE

Our future is so bright that we have to wear shades! WCMS Student Council attended We Day at the Excel Energy Center in St. Paul, MN. The theme for the day was EMPOWERMENT.
The day was spent with over 18,000 students, educators, motivational speakers and celebrities. The first period of our day was spend learning about Economic Empowerment. Second Period‚Äôs theme was Empowerment Through Technology and innovation. Social Empowerment was third period. The day was rounded out with a lesson on Education is Empowerment.
There is a small word right in the middle of that big word empoWErment that makes it all possible, WE.
